ugh knowledge of ancient sources with innovative new approaches grounded in recent economic historiography to provide a detailed picture of the Greek economy between the last century of the Archaic Age and the closing of the Hellenistic period. Focusing on the city-state, which he sees as the most important economic institution in the Greek world, Bresson addresses all of the city-states rather than only Athens.An expanded and updated English edition of an acclaimed work originally published in French, the book offers a groundbreaking new theoretical framework for studying the economy of ancient Greece; presents a masterful survey and analysis of the most important economic institutions, resources, and other factors; and addresses some major historiographical debates. Among the many topics covered are climate, demography, transportation, agricultural production, market institutions, money and credit, taxes, exchange, long-distance trade, and economic growth.The result is an unparalleled demonstration that, unlike just a generation ago, it is possible today to study the ancient Greek economy as an economy and not merely as a secondary aspect of social or political history. This is essential reading for students, historians of antiquity, and economic historians of all periods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aCities and towns, AncientzGreece. 0aUrban economics. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh1 aRendall, Steven.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066753008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311066259708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311044418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311066592508iTitle is p